alternatives.transcript: Hi there. This video is going to be a very quick introduction to the Emacs editor which is one of the standard editors on the NIF system and in fact most Unix systems. It's a very old editor but it has a ton of functionality once you get used to using it. There's definitely a learning curve to using Emacs but it's, once you learn it, you can do lots and lots of different things. Now you may have to bear with me in this video because I am not an Emacs user myself. I use VIM primarily, so I may not understand quite some of the commands I'm about to try to show you. But we will do the best we can the best we can with this. So if we type emacs and then hello dot c will open up the file. You can go around the file with the arrow keys, you're already ready to type, you can just type something else, print f and then hello one or something like that. I think if you wanna set it so that it makes your indentation four characters, you have to do that in a settings file. And then you can, you can, just do the change, make the changes you want and save it. How do you save in Emacs? Well, you do, you use what we call the, actually in this case I believe use control to save. So it's actually control x and it'll say what the command that you're starting down here is and control s will save and that's how you save. To quit, you do control x control c and you can quit like that. So let's open it back up again and notice that I did save my work here and I can just go and delete that if I want to. There is a command to delete the entire line, I just don't know what it is. But, you'll notice up here that there is a menu bar, up here like this and, it's it's a little weird, that should not have scrolled, but it's a little weird because there's no way to use the mouse if you're SSH ing in to do this. Actually there may be, but, in this I don't know exactly how to do this, to do that. But what I do know is if you type the f 10 key and in my Mac I have to type function and then f 10, it, brings up the options and you can see down here it says, if you wanna do, any of these various, things you can do that. So if I type o, it'll get me to option, it'll say highlight active region, etcetera. If you ever get in the middle of a command and want to back out of it, control g will go and go quit and go back to, where you were before. So let's say I want to, add line numbers to this. There's another control key or another modifier key kind of like control called the meta key. On my Mac it doesn't work through SSH again, but what you can do is you can just type escape and that stands for the meta key. So if you ever are looking at Emacs tutorials or references and it says meta, just know oh I have to hit escape. And in this case we do escape x, then it's going to say okay give me like a written command and in this case I think the written command is, what is it for here? It's line num dash mode and that should actually, there we go. Now we've got line numbers in here. Okay, there are various ways to jump around the document. If you want to go to a particular line, let's say we wanted to go to line six, we can type meta which is escape and then lowercase g and then another g and it says go to line and we can type six and it will jump right to that line. If we wanna actually search for something, we just type control s and it does a search. So if I wanna search for hello, there it is and it comes up immediately that that's where we wanna go to. So, and in fact if you wanna type, let's say we wanted to find just, o, control s and then o, it will jump to the o and if you keep hitting control s again, it will go to the next, instance and then wrap around if you don't find it. So, that's the very very very basics for Emacs. It's a great editor, I don't use it much so that's why I don't really know what I'm doing in here. You can open multiple files at once, they're called buffers in Emacs and it is very powerful. In fact, there's an entire programming language list built into Emacs so you can make your own commands and make it do very very advanced things. So anyway, right now I will do control X, control C and it will ask me if I wanna save it. Let's say I save it and I type Y and it brings you back to the terminal. Thanks.
